articles.title: NASA Launches Mission to Study Earth’s Magnetic Shield
articles.summary: NASA’s newest mission, TRACERS, soon will begin studying how Earth’s magnetic shield protects our planet from the effects of space weather. Short for Tandem Reconnection and Cusp Electrodynamics Reconnaissance Satellites, the twin TRACERS spacecraft lifted off at 11:13 a.m. PDT (2:13 p.m. EDT) Wednesday aboard a SpaceX Falcon 9 rocket from Space Launch Complex 4 […]
articles.content:
NASA’s TRACERS (Tandem Reconnection and Cusp Electrodynamics Reconnaissance Satellites) mission launched at 2:13 p.m. EDT atop a SpaceX Falcon 9 rocket at Space Launch Complex 4 East at Vandenberg Space Force Base in California. Credit: SpaceX

NASA’s newest mission, TRACERS, soon will begin studying how Earth’s magnetic shield protects our planet from the effects of space weather. Short for Tandem Reconnection and Cusp Electrodynamics Reconnaissance Satellites, the twin TRACERS spacecraft lifted off at 11:13 a.m. PDT (2:13 p.m. EDT) Wednesday aboard a SpaceX Falcon 9 rocket from Space Launch Complex 4 East at Vandenberg Space Force Base in California.

“NASA is proud to launch TRACERS to demonstrate and expand American preeminence in space science research and technology,” said acting NASA Administrator Sean Duffy. “The TRACERS satellites will move us forward in decoding space weather and further our understanding of the connection between Earth and the Sun. This mission will yield breakthroughs that will advance our pursuit of the Moon, and subsequently, Mars.”

The twin satellites will fly one behind the other – following as closely as 10 seconds apart over the same location – and will take a record-breaking 3,000 measurements in one year to build a step-by-step picture of how magnetic reconnection changes over time.

Riding along with TRACERS aboard the Falcon 9 were NASA’s Athena EPIC (Economical Payload Integration Cost), PExT (Polylingual Experimental Terminal), and REAL (Relativistic Electron Atmospheric Loss) missions – three small satellites to demonstrate new technologies and gather scientific data. These three missions were successfully deployed, and mission controllers will work to contact them over the coming hours and days.

Ground controllers for the TRACERS mission established communications with the second of the two spacecraft at 3:43 p.m. PDT (6:43 p.m. EDT), about 3 hours after it separated from the rocket. During the next four weeks, TRACERS will undergo a commissioning period during which mission controllers will check out their instruments and systems.

Once cleared, the twin satellites will begin their 12-month prime mission to study a process called magnetic reconnection, answering key questions about how it shapes the impacts of the Sun and space weather on our daily lives.

“NASA’s heliophysics fleet helps to safeguard humanity’s home in space and understand the influence of our closest star, the Sun,” said Joe Westlake, heliophysics division director at NASA Headquarters in Washington. “By adding TRACERS to that fleet, we will gain a better understanding of those impacts right here at Earth.”

The two TRACERS spacecraft will orbit through an open region in Earth’s magnetic field near the North Pole, called the polar cusp. Here, TRACERS will investigate explosive magnetic events that happen when the Sun’s magnetic field – carried through space in a stream of solar material called the solar wind – collides with Earth’s magnetic field. This collision creates a buildup of energy that causes magnetic reconnection, when magnetic field lines snap and explosively realign, flinging away nearby particles at high speeds.

Flying through the polar cusp allows the TRACERS satellites to study the results of these magnetic explosions, measuring charged particles that race down into Earth’s atmosphere and collide with atmospheric gases – giving scientist the tools to reconstruct exactly how changes in the incoming solar wind affect how, and how quickly, energy and particles are coupled into near-Earth space.

“The successful launch of TRACERS is a tribute to many years of work by an excellent team,” said David Miles, TRACERS principal investigator at the University of Iowa. “TRACERS is set to transform our understanding of Earth’s magnetosphere. We’re excited to explore the dynamic processes driving space weather.”

Small Satellites Along for Ride

Athena EPIC is a pathfinder mission that will demonstrate NASA’s use of an innovative and configurable commercial SmallSat architecture to improve flexibility of payload designs, reduce launch schedule, and reduce overall costs in future missions, as well as the benefits of working collaboratively with federal partners. In addition to this demonstration for NASA, once the Athena EPIC satellite completes its two-week commissioning period, the mission will spend the next 12 months taking measurements of outgoing longwave radiation from Earth.

The PExT demonstration will test interoperability between commercial and government communication networks for the first time by demonstrating a wideband polylingual terminal in low Earth orbit. This terminal will use software-defined radios to jump between government and commercial networks, similar to cell phones roaming between providers on Earth. These terminals could allow future missions to switch seamlessly between networks and access new commercial services throughout its lifecycle in space.

The REAL mission is a CubeSat that will investigate how energetic electrons are scattered out of the Van Allen radiation belts and into Earth’s atmosphere. Shaped like concentric rings high above Earth’s equator, the Van Allen belts are composed of a mix of high-energy electrons and protons that are trapped in place by Earth’s magnetic field. Studying electrons and their interactions, REAL aims to improve our understanding of these energetic particles that can damage spacecraft and imperil astronauts who pass through them.

The TRACERS mission is led by David Miles at the University of Iowa with support from the Southwest Research Institute in San Antonio, Texas. NASA’s Heliophysics Explorers Program Office at the agency’s Goddard Space Flight Center in Greenbelt, Maryland, manages the mission for the Heliophysics Division at NASA Headquarters in Washington. The University of Iowa, Southwest Research Institute, University of California, Los Angeles, and the University of California, Berkeley, all lead instruments on TRACERS.

The Athena EPIC mission is led by NASA’s Langley Research Center in Hampton, Virginia, and is a partnership between National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, U.S. Space Force, and NovaWurks. Athena EPIC’s launch is supported by launch integrator SEOPS. The PExT demonstration is managed by NASA’s SCaN (Space Communications and Navigation) program in partnership with Johns Hopkins Applied Physics Laboratory, with launch support by York Space Systems. The REAL project is led by Dartmouth College in Hanover, New Hampshire, and is a partnership between Johns Hopkins Applied Physics Laboratory, Montana State University, and Boston University. Sponsored by NASA’s Heliophysics Division and CubeSat Launch Initiative, it was included through launch integrator Maverick Space Systems.

NASA’s Launch Services Program, based at the agency’s Kennedy Space Center in Florida, manages the VADR (Venture-class Acquisition of Dedicated and Rideshare) contract.

To learn more about TRACERS, visit:

https://nasa.gov/tracers

-end-

articles.personality_title: NASA launches new mission to explore Earth’s magnetic shield
articles.personality_presentation:
**Context**
Earth is surrounded by a magnetic shield that protects us from harmful space weather like solar winds and cosmic radiation. Understanding this shield better helps scientists protect satellites, communication systems, and even power grids.

**What happened**
NASA launched its latest mission called TRACERS, which stands for Tandem Reconnection and Cusp Electrodynamics Reconnaissance Satellites. Two small satellites lifted off together on a SpaceX Falcon 9 rocket from California. These twins will study how the magnetic shield works, especially where it reconnects and interacts with charged particles from the sun.

**Impact**
By closely observing these magnetic processes, TRACERS will provide valuable insights into how space weather affects Earth’s protection. This knowledge can improve forecasts of solar storms, helping to prevent damage to important technologies and keeping our planet safer.

**What's next step**
The twin satellites will begin their detailed observations soon after reaching orbit. Scientists will analyze the data to understand magnetic reconnection better—the process where magnetic fields break and reconnect, releasing energy. This will pave the way for future missions and improved space weather prediction.

**One-sentence takeaway**
NASA’s TRACERS mission is a big step forward in unlocking the secrets of Earth’s magnetic shield, helping protect our planet from space weather risks.
articles.personality_title_fr: La NASA lance une nouvelle mission pour explorer le bouclier magnétique de la Terre
articles.personality_presentation_fr:
**Contexte**
La Terre est protégée par un bouclier magnétique qui nous défend contre les intempéries spatiales comme les vents solaires et les radiations cosmiques. Mieux comprendre ce bouclier aide les scientifiques à protéger les satellites, les communications et les réseaux électriques.

**Ce qui s’est passé**
La NASA a lancé sa mission la plus récente appelée TRACERS, pour Tandem Reconnection and Cusp Electrodynamics Reconnaissance Satellites. Deux petits satellites jumeaux ont décollé ensemble à bord d'une fusée SpaceX Falcon 9 depuis la Californie. Ces satellites étudieront le fonctionnement du bouclier magnétique, notamment là où il se reconnecte et interagit avec les particules chargées du soleil.

**Impact**
En observant de près ces processus magnétiques, TRACERS fournira des informations précieuses sur la façon dont les intempéries spatiales affectent la protection de la Terre. Ces connaissances permettront d'améliorer les prévisions des tempêtes solaires et de mieux protéger les technologies essentielles.

**Prochaine étape**
Les deux satellites commenceront bientôt leurs observations détaillées en orbite. Les scientifiques analyseront les données pour mieux comprendre la reconnexion magnétique, un phénomène où les champs magnétiques se cassent et se reconnectent en libérant de l'énergie. Cela ouvrira la voie à de futures missions et à une meilleure prévision des intempéries spatiales.

**Conclusion en une phrase**
La mission TRACERS de la NASA est un grand pas pour percer les secrets du bouclier magnétique terrestre et protéger notre planète des risques liés à l’espace.
articles.personality_title_es: La NASA lanza nueva misión para explorar el escudo magnético de la Tierra
articles.personality_presentation_es:
**Contexto**
La Tierra está protegida por un escudo magnético que nos defiende de fenómenos espaciales dañinos como los vientos solares y la radiación cósmica. Entender mejor este escudo ayuda a los científicos a proteger satélites, comunicaciones y redes eléctricas.

**Qué pasó**
La NASA lanzó su misión más reciente llamada TRACERS, que significa Satélites Gemelos para el Reconocimiento de la Reconciliación y Electrodinámica de la Cúspide. Dos pequeños satélites gemelos despegaron juntos a bordo de un cohete SpaceX Falcon 9 desde California. Estos satélites estudiarán cómo funciona el escudo magnético, especialmente donde se reconecta e interactúa con partículas solares cargadas.

**Impacto**
Al observar de cerca estos procesos magnéticos, TRACERS brindará información valiosa sobre cómo el clima espacial afecta la protección de la Tierra. Este conocimiento puede mejorar las predicciones de tormentas solares y ayudar a prevenir daños en tecnologías importantes.

**Próximo paso**
Los satélites gemelos comenzarán pronto sus observaciones detalladas en órbita. Los científicos analizarán los datos para entender mejor la reconciliación magnética, un proceso donde los campos magnéticos se rompen y reconectan liberando energía. Esto abrirá camino a futuras misiones y mejores predicciones del clima espacial.

**Resumen en una frase**
La misión TRACERS de la NASA es un gran avance para descubrir los secretos del escudo magnético de la Tierra y proteger nuestro planeta de los riesgos del clima espacial.

articles.title: NASA Sets Launch Coverage for Earth-Tracking NISAR Satellite
articles.summary: NASA will provide live coverage of launch activities for NISAR (NASA-ISRO Synthetic Aperture Radar), which is set to lift off at 8:10 a.m. EDT (5:40 p.m. IST), Wednesday, July 30, from Satish Dhawan Space Centre on India’s southeastern coast. A collaboration between NASA and the Indian Space Research Organisation (ISRO), the first-of-its-kind satellite will lift […]
articles.content:
A collaboration between NASA and the Indian Space Research Organisation, NISAR will use synthetic aperture radar to monitor nearly all the planet’s land- and ice-covered surfaces twice every 12 days. Credit: NASA/JPL-Caltech

NASA will provide live coverage of launch activities for NISAR (NASA-ISRO Synthetic Aperture Radar), which is set to lift off at 8:10 a.m. EDT (5:40 p.m. IST), Wednesday, July 30, from Satish Dhawan Space Centre on India’s southeastern coast.

A collaboration between NASA and the Indian Space Research Organisation (ISRO), the first-of-its-kind satellite will lift off aboard an ISRO Geosynchronous Satellite Launch Vehicle on a mission to scan nearly all the Earth’s land and ice surfaces twice every 12 days.

Watch live coverage of the launch on NASA+ and the agency’s YouTube channel. Learn how to watch NASA content through a variety of platforms, including social media.

With its two radar instruments — an S-band system provided by ISRO and an L-band system provided by NASA — the NISAR mission will provide high-resolution data to help decision-makers, communities, and scientists monitor major infrastructure, agricultural fields, and movement of land and ice surfaces.

Hailed as a critical part of a pioneering year for United States – India civil space cooperation by President Trump and Prime Minister Modi during their visit in Washington in February, the NISAR launch will advance U.S. – India cooperation and benefit the U.S. in areas such as agriculture and preparation and response to disasters like hurricanes, floods, and volcanic eruptions.

NASA’s mission coverage is as follows (all times Eastern and subject to change based on real-time operations):

Monday, July 28

12 p.m. – Prelaunch teleconference with the following participants:

Karen St. Germain, director of Earth science, NASA Headquarters

Gerald Bawden, NISAR program scientist, NASA Headquarters

Shanna McClain, Disasters program manager, NASA Headquarters

Phil Barela, NISAR project manager, NASA Jet Propulsion Laboratory (JPL)

Marco Lavalle, NISAR deputy project scientist, NASA JPL

The teleconference will stream on JPL’s YouTube Channel.

Members of the media may ask questions via phone during the teleconference. To register, media must provide their name and affiliation by 4 p.m. on Sunday, July 27, to Rexana Vizza at: rexana.v.vizza@jpl.nasa.gov. Questions may also be asked via social media with the hashtag #AskNISAR.

Wednesday, July 30

7 a.m. – Launch coverage begins on NASA+ and YouTube.

The launch broadcast begins from NASA’s Jet Propulsion Laboratory in Southern California, where the U.S. portion of the mission is managed.

Follow launch events on NASA’s NISAR blog.

Watch, Engage on Social Media

You can also stay connected by following and tagging these accounts:

X: @NASA, @NASAEarth, @NASAJPL

Facebook: NASA, NASA Earth, NASA JPL

Instagram: @NASA, @NASAEarth, @NASAJPL

Additional Resources

The NISAR press kit features deeper dives into the mission as well as its science and technology.

Explore NISAR videos as well as NISAR animations and b-roll media reel.

The NISAR mission is the first joint satellite mission between NASA and ISRO, marking a new chapter in the growing collaboration between the two space agencies. The launch of NISAR, years in the making, builds on a strong heritage of successful programs, including Chandrayaan-1 and the recent Axiom Mission-4, which saw ISRO and NASA astronauts living and working together aboard the International Space Station for the first time.

Learn more about the mission at:

https://science.nasa.gov/mission/nisar

-end-

Elizabeth Vlock / Karen Fox

Headquarters, Washington

202-358-1600

elizabeth.a.vlock@nasa.gov / karen.c.fox@nasa.gov

Andrew Wang / Jane J. Lee

Jet Propulsion Laboratory, Pasadena, Calif.

626-379-6874 / 818-354-0307

andrew.wang@jpl.nasa.gov / jane.j.lee@jpl.nasa.gov

articles.personality_title: NASA and India team up to launch a groundbreaking Earth-watching satellite
articles.personality_presentation:
**Context**
NASA and the Indian Space Research Organisation (ISRO) are joining forces on a special satellite mission called NISAR. This satellite will use synthetic aperture radar, a technology that creates detailed images by bouncing radar waves off Earth, to keep a close eye on almost all the planet’s land and ice surfaces.

**What happened**
NISAR is set to launch on July 30, with NASA providing live coverage of the event from the Satish Dhawan Space Centre in India. This launch marks the first time NASA and ISRO have collaborated on a satellite using this advanced radar technology.

**Impact**
Once in orbit, NISAR will scan the Earth twice every 12 days, helping scientists track changes in forests, glaciers, and landforms. This constant monitoring can improve our understanding of climate change and help manage natural resources more wisely.

**What's next step**
After launch, teams from NASA and ISRO will work together to test and operate the satellite, making sure it collects clear and useful data. They will then share this information with researchers worldwide to support environmental protection and disaster response.

**One-sentence takeaway**
This international partnership is launching a powerful new tool to watch and protect our planet like never before.
articles.personality_title_fr: La NASA et l'Inde s'associent pour lancer un satellite révolutionnaire d'observation de la Terre
articles.personality_presentation_fr:
**Contexte**
La NASA et l'Organisation indienne de recherche spatiale (ISRO) unissent leurs forces pour une mission satellitaire spéciale nommée NISAR. Ce satellite utilisera un radar à synthèse d'ouverture, une technologie qui crée des images détaillées en envoyant des ondes radar vers la Terre, pour surveiller de près presque toutes les surfaces terrestres et glacées de la planète.

**Ce qui s'est passé**
Le lancement de NISAR est prévu pour le 30 juillet, avec une couverture en direct assurée par la NASA depuis le centre spatial Satish Dhawan en Inde. Ce lancement marque la première collaboration entre la NASA et l'ISRO sur un satellite utilisant cette technologie radar avancée.

**Impact**
Une fois en orbite, NISAR scannera la Terre deux fois tous les 12 jours, aidant les scientifiques à suivre les changements dans les forêts, les glaciers et les reliefs. Cette surveillance constante peut améliorer notre compréhension du changement climatique et aider à gérer les ressources naturelles plus intelligemment.

**Prochaine étape**
Après le lancement, les équipes de la NASA et de l'ISRO travailleront ensemble pour tester et exploiter le satellite, en s'assurant qu'il collecte des données claires et utiles. Elles partageront ensuite ces informations avec les chercheurs du monde entier pour soutenir la protection de l'environnement et la gestion des catastrophes.

**Conclusion en une phrase**
Ce partenariat international lance un outil puissant pour observer et protéger notre planète comme jamais auparavant.

articles.title: NASA Astronaut Jonny Kim, Axiom Mission 4 Commander Peggy Whitson Conduct Research in Space
articles.summary: In this photo from June 28, 2025, Expedition 73 flight engineer Jonny Kim and former NASA astronaut and director of human spaceflight at Axiom Space Peggy Whitson work together inside the International Space Station’s Destiny laboratory module setting up hardware for cancer research. The hardware is used to culture patient-derived cancer cells, model their growth […]
articles.content:
JAXA (Japan Aerospace Exploration Agency)/Takuya Onishi

In this photo from June 28, 2025, Expedition 73 flight engineer Jonny Kim and former NASA astronaut and director of human spaceflight at Axiom Space Peggy Whitson work together inside the International Space Station’s Destiny laboratory module setting up hardware for cancer research.

The hardware is used to culture patient-derived cancer cells, model their growth in microgravity, and test a state-of-the-art fluorescence microscope. Results of this study may lead to earlier cancer detection methods, development of advanced cancer treatments, and promote future stem cell research in space.

Whitson returned to Earth on July 15, 2025, with fellow Axiom Mission 4 crew members ISRO (Indian Space Research Organisation) astronaut Shubhanshu Shukla, ESA (European Space Agency) project astronaut Sławosz Uznański-Wiśniewski of Poland, and Hungarian to Orbit (HUNOR) astronaut Tibor Kapu of Hungary. They completed about two and a half weeks in space.

Image credit: JAXA (Japan Aerospace Exploration Agency)/Takuya Onishi
articles.reasoning: The article highlights astronauts conducting cancer research aboard the International Space Station, representing a positive scientific endeavor with potential medical benefits. This kind of research can inspire hope for medical advances and showcases human cooperation in space exploration.
articles.personality_title: Astronauts conduct cancer research aboard the International Space Station
articles.personality_presentation:
**Context**
NASA astronauts Jonny Kim and Peggy Whitson are aboard the International Space Station (ISS), using its unique environment to study cancer cells. The ISS offers microgravity, which means very low gravity, allowing scientists to observe how cancer grows in space.

**What happened**
On June 28, 2025, Kim and Whitson worked inside the ISS’s Destiny laboratory to set up special equipment for cancer research. This hardware helps grow cancer cells taken from patients, so researchers can see how they behave in space. They also tested a new type of microscope that uses fluorescence, which helps highlight parts of the cells.

**Impact**
Studying cancer cells in microgravity can reveal new insights that aren’t possible on Earth. This research could lead to better understanding of cancer growth and, eventually, improved treatments. It also shows how astronauts can support important medical science while exploring space.

**What's next step**
The research team will analyze the data collected from these experiments and continue refining the tools used. Future missions will build on this work to deepen our knowledge of cancer and test other medical studies in space.

**One-sentence takeaway**
Space-based cancer research is opening new doors to medical breakthroughs, thanks to the teamwork and dedication of astronauts aboard the ISS.
articles.personality_title_fr: Des astronautes mènent des recherches sur le cancer à bord de la Station spatiale internationale
articles.personality_presentation_fr:

Les astronautes de la NASA Jonny Kim et Peggy Whitson sont à bord de la Station spatiale internationale (ISS), utilisant cet environnement unique pour étudier les cellules cancéreuses. L'ISS offre une microgravité, c'est-à-dire une gravité très faible, permettant aux scientifiques d'observer comment le cancer se développe dans l'espace.

**Ce qui s'est passé**
Le 28 juin 2025, Kim et Whitson ont travaillé à l'intérieur du laboratoire Destiny de l'ISS pour installer un équipement spécial destiné à la recherche sur le cancer. Ce matériel aide à cultiver des cellules cancéreuses prélevées sur des patients, afin que les chercheurs puissent étudier leur comportement dans l'espace. Ils ont aussi testé un nouveau type de microscope utilisant la fluorescence, qui permet de mieux visualiser les parties des cellules.

**Impact**
Étudier les cellules cancéreuses en microgravité peut révéler des informations nouvelles impossibles à obtenir sur Terre. Cette recherche pourrait conduire à une meilleure compréhension de la croissance du cancer et, à terme, à de meilleurs traitements. Elle montre aussi comment les astronautes peuvent soutenir la science médicale importante tout en explorant l'espace.

**Prochaine étape**
L'équipe de recherche analysera les données récoltées et continuera à améliorer les outils utilisés. Les missions futures s'appuieront sur ce travail pour approfondir nos connaissances sur le cancer et tester d'autres études médicales dans l'espace.

**Résumé en une phrase**
La recherche sur le cancer en microgravité ouvre de nouvelles perspectives médicales grâce au travail d'équipe et à l'engagement des astronautes à bord de l'ISS.
articles.personality_title_es: Astronautas realizan investigaciones sobre el cáncer a bordo de la Estación Espacial Internacional
articles.personality_presentation_es:
**Contexto**
Los astronautas de la NASA Jonny Kim y Peggy Whitson están en la Estación Espacial Internacional (ISS), utilizando su entorno único para estudiar células cancerosas. La ISS ofrece microgravedad, es decir, muy baja gravedad, lo que permite a los científicos observar cómo crece el cáncer en el espacio.

**Qué sucedió**
El 28 de junio de 2025, Kim y Whitson trabajaron dentro del laboratorio Destiny de la ISS para instalar un equipo especial para la investigación del cáncer. Este hardware ayuda a cultivar células cancerosas obtenidas de pacientes, para que los investigadores puedan ver cómo se comportan en el espacio. También probaron un nuevo tipo de microscopio que utiliza fluorescencia para resaltar partes de las células.

**Impacto**
Estudiar células cancerosas en microgravedad puede revelar nuevos conocimientos que no son posibles en la Tierra. Esta investigación podría conducir a una mejor comprensión del crecimiento del cáncer y, eventualmente, a tratamientos mejorados. También demuestra cómo los astronautas pueden apoyar importantes ciencias médicas mientras exploran el espacio.

**Próximo paso**
El equipo de investigación analizará los datos recogidos en estos experimentos y continuará perfeccionando las herramientas utilizadas. Las futuras misiones continuarán este trabajo para profundizar nuestro conocimiento sobre el cáncer y probar otros estudios médicos en el espacio.

**Conclusión en una frase**
La investigación del cáncer en el espacio está abriendo nuevas puertas a avances médicos, gracias al trabajo en equipo y la dedicación de los astronautas a bordo de la ISS.

articles.title: NASA Scientist Finds Predicted Companion Star to Betelgeuse
articles.summary: A century-old hypothesis that Betelgeuse, the 10th brightest star in our night sky, is orbited by a very close companion star was proved true by a team of astrophysicists led by a scientist at NASA’s Ames Research Center in California’s Silicon Valley. The research published in The Astrophysical Journal Letters in the paper “Probable Direct […]
articles.content:
An image of Betelgeuse, the yellow-red star, and the signature of its close companion, the faint blue object. Data: NASA/JPL/NOIRlab. Visualization: NOIRLAB.

A century-old hypothesis that Betelgeuse, the 10th brightest star in our night sky, is orbited by a very close companion star was proved true by a team of astrophysicists led by a scientist at NASA’s Ames Research Center in California’s Silicon Valley.

The research published in The Astrophysical Journal Letters in the paper “Probable Direct Imaging Discovery of the Stellar Companion to Betelgeuse.”

Fluctuations in the brightness and measured velocity of Betelgeuse, the closest red supergiant star to Earth, had long presented clues that it may have a partner, but the bigger star’s intense glow made direct observations of any fainter neighbors nearly impossible.

Two recent studies by other teams of astronomers reignited the companion star hypothesis by using more than 100 years of Betelgeuse observations to provide predictions of the companion’s location and brightness.

If the smaller star did exist, the location predictions suggested that scientists had a window of just a few months to observe the companion star at its widest separation from Betelgeuse, as it orbited near the visible edge of the supergiant. After that, they would have to wait another three years for it to orbit to the other side and again leave the overpowering glow of its larger companion.

Searches for the companion were initially made using space-based telescopes, because observing through Earth’s atmosphere can blur images of astronomical objects. But these efforts did not detect the companion.

Steve Howell, a senior research scientist at Ames, recognized the ground-based Gemini North telescope in Hawai’i, one of the largest in the world, paired with a special, high-resolution camera built by NASA, had the potential to directly observe the close companion to Betelgeuse, despite the atmospheric blurring.

Officially called the ‘Alopeke speckle instrument, the advanced imaging camera let them obtain many thousands of short exposures to measure the atmospheric interference in their data and remove it with detailed image processing, providing an image of Betelgeuse and its companion.

Howell’s team detected the very faint companion star right where it was predicted to be, orbiting very close to the outer edge of Betelgeuse.

“I hope our discovery excites other astrophysicists about the robust power of ground-based telescopes and speckle imagers – a key to opening new observational windows,” said Howell. “This can help unlock the great mysteries in our universe.”

To start, this discovery of a close companion to Betelgeuse may explain why other similar red supergiant stars undergo periodic changes in their brightness on the scale of many years.

Howell plans to continue observations of Betelgeuse’s stellar companion to better understand its nature. The companion star will again return to its greatest separation from Betelgeuse in November 2027, a time when it will be easiest to detect.

Having found the long-anticipated companion star, Howell turned to giving it a name. The traditional star name “Betelgeuse” derives from Arabic, meaning “the hand of al-Jawza’,” a female figure in old Arabian legend. Fittingly, Howell’s team named the orbiting companion “Siwarha,” meaning “her bracelet.”

Photo of the constellation Orion, showing the location of Betelgeuse – and its newfound companion star. NOIRLab/Eckhard Slawik

The NASA–National Science Foundation Exoplanet Observational Research Program (NN-EXPLORE) is a joint initiative to advance U.S. exoplanet science by providing the community with access to cutting-edge, ground-based observational facilities. Managed by NASA’s Exoplanet Exploration Program, NN-EXPLORE supports and enhances the scientific return of space missions such as Kepler, TESS (Transiting Exoplanet Survey Satellite), Hubble Space Telescope, and James Webb Space Telescope by enabling essential follow-up observations from the ground—creating strong synergies between space-based discoveries and ground-based characterization. NASA’s Exoplanet Exploration Program is located at the agency’s Jet Propulsion Laboratory.

To learn more about NN-EXPLORE, visit:

https://exoplanets.nasa.gov/exep/NNExplore/overview

articles.personality_title: NASA scientist confirms companion star orbiting Betelgeuse after 100 years
articles.personality_presentation:
**Context**
Betelgeuse is one of the brightest stars in our night sky, known for its yellow-red glow. For over a century, scientists suspected that it might have a close companion star, but this idea hadn't been proven.

**What happened**
A team of astrophysicists led by a NASA scientist at the Ames Research Center in California confirmed the existence of this companion star. They published their findings in The Astrophysical Journal Letters, showing clear evidence of a faint blue star orbiting very close to Betelgeuse.

**Impact**
This discovery is a big deal for scientists because it confirms a long-standing theory and helps us understand more about how stars interact and evolve. It also sparks excitement about what else we might learn from stars near us in space.

**What's next step**
Researchers will now study the relationship between Betelgeuse and its companion in more detail. This could reveal new insights into star life cycles and offer clues about the future behavior of Betelgeuse, which is known for its dramatic changes.

**One-sentence takeaway**
After 100 years, scientists have finally confirmed Betelgeuse has a close companion star, opening new doors to understanding our cosmic neighborhood.
articles.personality_title_fr: Un scientifique de la NASA confirme l'étoile compagne orbitant autour de Bételgeuse après 100 ans
articles.personality_presentation_fr:
**Contexte**
Bételgeuse est l'une des étoiles les plus brillantes dans notre ciel nocturne, connue pour sa lueur jaune-rouge. Depuis plus d'un siècle, les scientifiques soupçonnaient qu'elle pourrait avoir une étoile compagne proche, mais cette idée n'avait pas été prouvée.

**Ce qui s'est passé**
Une équipe d'astrophysiciens dirigée par un scientifique de la NASA au Centre de recherche Ames en Californie a confirmé l'existence de cette étoile compagne. Ils ont publié leurs résultats dans The Astrophysical Journal Letters, montrant des preuves claires d'une étoile bleue faible orbitant très près de Bételgeuse.

**Impact**
Cette découverte est importante pour les scientifiques car elle confirme une théorie ancienne et nous aide à mieux comprendre comment les étoiles interagissent et évoluent. Elle suscite aussi de l'enthousiasme sur ce que nous pourrions apprendre d'autres étoiles proches dans l'espace.

**Prochaine étape**
Les chercheurs vont maintenant étudier plus en détail la relation entre Bételgeuse et son compagnon. Cela pourrait révéler de nouvelles informations sur le cycle de vie des étoiles et donner des indices sur le comportement futur de Bételgeuse, connue pour ses changements spectaculaires.

**Résumé en une phrase**
Après 100 ans, les scientifiques ont enfin confirmé que Bételgeuse a une étoile compagne proche, ouvrant de nouvelles perspectives pour comprendre notre voisinage cosmique.
articles.personality_title_es: Científico de la NASA confirma estrella compañera orbitando Betelgeuse después de 100 años
articles.personality_presentation_es:
**Contexto**
Betelgeuse es una de las estrellas más brillantes en nuestro cielo nocturno, conocida por su brillo amarillo-rojo. Durante más de un siglo, los científicos sospecharon que podría tener una estrella compañera cercana, pero esta idea no se había comprobado.

**Qué pasó**
Un equipo de astrofísicos liderado por un científico de la NASA en el Centro de Investigación Ames en California confirmó la existencia de esta estrella compañera. Publicaron sus hallazgos en The Astrophysical Journal Letters, mostrando evidencia clara de una estrella azul tenue orbitando muy cerca de Betelgeuse.

**Impacto**
Este descubrimiento es muy importante para los científicos porque confirma una teoría antigua y nos ayuda a entender mejor cómo interactúan y evolucionan las estrellas. También despierta entusiasmo sobre qué más podríamos aprender de las estrellas cercanas en el espacio.

**Próximo paso**
Los investigadores ahora estudiarán la relación entre Betelgeuse y su compañera en más detalle. Esto podría revelar nuevas ideas sobre los ciclos de vida de las estrellas y ofrecer pistas sobre el comportamiento futuro de Betelgeuse, conocida por sus cambios dramáticos.

**Conclusión en una frase**
Después de 100 años, los científicos finalmente confirmaron que Betelgeuse tiene una estrella compañera cercana, abriendo nuevas puertas para entender nuestro vecindario cósmico.
